{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17521944","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17521944"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T14:38:58+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T14:38:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13784"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13784","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13784"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.02,0.58,0.03,0.01,0.35]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6402"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"106239"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6402","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6402"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13784"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88707"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"8"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"27"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1193"},{"type":"tags","id":"2382"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4963"},{"type":"tags","id":"4976"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11635"},{"type":"tags","id":"11636"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"12598"},{"type":"contributions","id":"30649"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42931"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44002"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"106239","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/106239"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 42-year-old man presents to the rural GP lead Emergency Department with severe pain and blurred vision in his left eye. He works in an industrial factory and reports that 30 minutes ago, a pipe burst and sprayed liquid onto his face. He immediately irrigated his eyes at work. He has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears distressed. His vital signs are within normal limits. Visual acuity is 6/6 in the right eye and 6/18 in the left eye. The conjunctiva of the left eye is injected. Fluorescein staining shows a 4 mm epithelial defect. The pH of the left eye is 10.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate immediate management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Measure intraocular pressure","Evert eyelids and irrigate with 1L 0.9% saline","Apply chloramphenicol ointment","Obtain CT orbits","Urgent referral for opthalmology assessment"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EChemical injuries to the eye are an ophthalmic emergency. Immediate, copious irrigation is the priority to normalise the pH and minimise damage to ocular structures. At least 30 minutes of irrigation with normal saline or lactated Ringer\u0027s solution is required. In this case, the patient\u0027s left eye pH is 10, indicating an alkaline injury. \u003Cstrong\u003EIrrigation with 1L 0.9% saline \u003C/strong\u003Eshould be the initial priority with the \u003Cstrong\u003Eeyelids everted\u003C/strong\u003E to remove any retained particulate matter. This can be achieved using a Morgan Lens. The pH of the eye should then be re-checked and irrigation continue until the pH is acceptable. Alkali burns typically require continuous irrigation for 30 minutes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAfter irrigation is complete, \u003Cstrong\u003Eintraocular pressure\u003C/strong\u003E can be measured, as this may be elevated in severe chemical injuries. However, this is not the immediate priority.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOnce the pH has normalised, \u003Cstrong\u003Echloramphenicol ointment\u003C/strong\u003E or other topical antibiotics may be applied to prevent infection. This is not done before or during irrigation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESevere chemical injuries causing globe rupture may require \u003Cstrong\u003ECT orbits\u003C/strong\u003E, but there is no indication of globe rupture in this case. The patient has no proptosis, and his visual acuity, while reduced, is not severely impaired.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis patient will require \u003Cstrong\u003Eurgent ophthalmology assessment\u003C/strong\u003E. Severe chemical injuries can cause long-term complications such as corneal scarring, glaucoma and cataracts. However, urgent irrigation takes precedence over referral.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Immediate copious irrigation is the priority in managing chemical eye injuries, even before examination.","The severity of chemical eye injuries is determined by the pH, with alkaline substances generally causing more severe injuries than acids.","Careful eversion of the eyelids is important to remove any retained particulate matter."],"references":["Ophthalmology Network Eye Emergency Manual. In: Agency for Clinical Innovation [online]. 2023. Available at: https://aci.health.nsw.gov.au/__data/assets/pdf_file/0013/155011/ACI-Eye-Emergency-Manual.pdf"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88707"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13784"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88707","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/88707"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-06-17T07:40:02+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-17T07:40:02+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6402"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"106239"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"